                    "company": "UCD Sutherland School of Law",
                    "description": "My research project tests the potential of collective approaches in enhancing the effectiveness of agri-environmental policies aimed at enhancing biodiversity and landscape values in agricultural landscapes. Within the EU context, the regulatory framework governing such policies is found most prominently in the EU Birds & Habitats Directive as well as the Common Agricultural Policy. \n\nThe study takes the Netherlands as a case study, where, in 2016, a range of regulatory roles such as the distributing of agri-environmental subsidies, as well as monitoring of the results and, where necessary, enforcing set rules, were shifted from the state level to private-led \u2018environmental cooperatives\u2019. There are currently forty, region-based, environmental cooperatives in place, composed of groups of farmers and other stakeholders, such as environmental organizations and members of civil society. Overarching policy objectives are still set at the state level, but the individual cooperatives enjoy great flexibility in deciding the most effective way to realise these objectives locally, based on the preferences and capabilities of the group. \n\nWhile the potential merits of the cooperative approach for combating biodiversity loss and landscape deterioration in agricultural contexts has been recognized in the literature, little attention has been given to the benefits and risks of the move towards self-regulation from a law and governance perspective. Employing qualitative research methods, this research examines and critically evaluates the role and functioning of environmental cooperatives in the nature governance landscape, focusing particularly on their role in the implementation of agri-environmental rules and policy objectives flowing from the EU level, to the individual farmer level. \n\nMy research is part of European Research Council funded Effective Nature Laws project.",
                    "title": "PhD Researcher",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
